<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> APPLE IN TALKS TO BUY BEATS <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Apple is said to be in discussions to buy Beats Electronics, the company behind the popular Beats by Dr. Dre headphones, for $3.2 billion, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/apple-said-to-be-in-talks-to-buy-beats-for-3-2-billion">Ben Sisario, Brian X. Chen and David Gelles write in DealBook</a></b>. The deal, which would also include the new Beats Music streaming service, would be the biggest acquisition in Appleâs history and could suggest an effort to shake up its approach to digital music.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Apple, âthe deal could point to a a <b>headlong move into the frontier of streaming music</b>,â they write. âThe purchase would also give Apple a hot product and an even hotter brand.â Annual sales of Beats products have been estimated at more than $1.5 billion. Last year, <b>the private equity firm Carlyle Group invested $500 million in Beats</b>, valuing the company at more than $1 billion. The deal could potentially fit into a larger strategy for Apple, which has struggled in developing new products.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> AD AGENCIES CALL OFF MERGER <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The ad giants Omnicom Group and Publicis Groupe called off their $35 billion merger on Thursday, âbringing a premature end to a deal that would have created the largest advertising company in the world,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/ad-agency-giants-said-to-call-off-35-billion-merger">David Gelles writes in DealBook</a></b>. âA mix of clashing personalities, disagreements about how the companies would be integrated and complications over legal and tax issues derailed the deal nine months after it was announced.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>When the merger was announced last summer</b>, it was billed as a chance to create an international powerhouse with the capabilities to serve clients with a mix of digital and traditional agencies. The deal was also seen as a response to the technological transformation in the industry. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>But a number of issues appear to have derailed the deal</b>. One unresolved issue was which company would be acquiring the other one. Another holdup was that China had not granted the deal regulatory approval. No termination fees will be paid as a result of the dealâs collapse.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> COMPANIES WEIGH MOVING ABROAD <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Pfizerâs attempt to escape the United States corporate tax rate by acquiring the British drug maker AstraZeneca has inspired a wave of activity at other big American corporations, at investment banks and on Capitol Hill, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/pfizer-plan-to-go-to-london-spurs-other-companies-to-consider-moving-abroad">David Gelles writes in DealBook</a></b>. If Pfizerâs $106 billion offer for AstraZeneca is successful, Pfizer would become a British company, reducing its tax bill by at least $1 billion a year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The promise of such savings</b> has many other big companies, including Walgreen, wondering whether they could also reincorporate overseas. For their part, investment bankers and lawyers are urging clients to act quickly <b>before rules change</b>. In Washington, lawmakers have started examining what legislation could be drafted to stop these so-called inversions, the deals through which United States companies acquire an overseas competitor and reincorporate abroad. One such bill could be introduced as early as next week.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The <b>Job Openings and Labor Turnover Survey</b> comes out at 10 a.m. The <b>wholesale trade report</b> also comes out at 10 a.m. <b>Richard W. Fisher</b>, president of the Dallas Fed, gives a speech on monetary policy in New Orleans at noon. <b>Mohamed A. El-Erian</b>, formerly chief executive and co-chief investment officer of Pimco, is on CNBC at 3:10 p.m. Treasury Secretary <b>Jacob J. Lew</b> is on Bloomberg TV at 9 p.m. Happy birthday, <b>Billy Joel</b>, who is turning 65. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> GEITHNER REVISITED <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Timothy F. Geithner âvery much wants to be understood,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/11/magazine/what-timothy-geithner-really-thinks.html">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes</a></b> in this weekâs New York Times Magazine cover article. Since he stepped down as Treasury secretary last year, Mr. Geithner has largely remained out of the public eye. But now, with his book âStress Test: Reflections on Financial Crises,â set to come out next week, <b>he is breaking his silence</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Sorkin writes</b>: âThrough it all, Geithner has maintained that saving the banks was the only way to protect the U.S. economic system and, by extension, its taxpayers.â He adds, âPerhaps the main challenge that Geithner has found in selling his argument is that to believe that the bailout truly worked, <b>you have to believe that the other side of the cliff would have been worse</b>. This makes his argument something of a counterfactual one, a hypothesis that will always be open to interpretation.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Hereâs a teaser from the article</b>: During a lunch at CafÃ© Centro, near Grand Central Terminal, Geithner shared a story, which also appears in his book, about seeking advice from former President Bill Clinton on how to pursue a more populist strategy. âYou could take Lloyd Blankfein into a dark alley,â Clinton said, âand slit his throat, and it would satisfy them for about two days. Then the blood lust would rise again.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Donât have time to read the full article</b>? Here are <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/08/5-takeaways-from-magazine-article-on-geithner-and-the-financial-crisis">several takeaways</a></b>.</p>
